At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements into an Iraq consumed by civil war as "irresponsible and catastrophic decision in its consequences."
However, the following months showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only possible and likely to be successful to such an extent that the newspapers at present are not talking about Iraq at all.
This has not improved Bush's reputation, which says, objectively speaking, he left his successor a far more favourable final situation than could be expected.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan the miracle will reproduce
It was once again the campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reluctance despite the habit of subordination.
He requested 40,000 men to make the situation more favourable.
The president hesitated for three months, but in the absence of a better option, he cheated at least the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He succeeded in extirpating Europe's 5 000 additional promises, even if it had 10,000 originally.
What brings the most problems in Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to remove the Afghan armies within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. All Obama's doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a half increase will bring the same fruit as the growth in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out by the exact opposite - no one can be relied on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders to the day according to their arrangements.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will only remain powder in the eyes behind which will proliferate patriarchal ethnic relations.
It is uniquely complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity about the relations, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "ready-to-do" state, which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of the Obama strategy is perplexed by its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart and out of reality can be persuaded that the small soldiers sent in the tumult of the war for their "soon return to the house" will bring a real miracle.
From a political point of view, defining a date for withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will view it as an indirect abstention from the US defeat.
The last NATO summit has shown that the Europeans' willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is in the negative direction.
European policies do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of Hindu Kush.
Another factor that can radically alter the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the enhanced sanctions do not have an effect on Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult issue of a resolution of the problem through the use of military force.
For example, there will be a need to respond when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of Afghanistan's troops.
However, each solution of this type will result in a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
Obama's only rustine is the fact that he remains three years until the presidential elections, and therefore there is still enough time left for him to plan a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
