Czech discovery: a substance that works on "endurant" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists tests new combinations that can slow the proliferation of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed a drug immunity.
This reality, in some cases, takes over the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on the current variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
However, the life of the sick can be radically extended through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, consumption results in a series of side effects.
In addition, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have any effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are a combination of bore, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all medicines used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of molecular mechanics of their bindings on virus proteins.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms and linked by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protein is a protein of the HIV virus that is indispensable to the life cycle of the virus.
