The Chinese authorities have entrusted the police with the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous tendency for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced women pregnant with a second child to have an abortion.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high ratio of boys and girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the policy of the single child.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already single children -- and in 2007, they have softened much of their hard slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, professor at the Institute of Population Research, at the University of Beijing, said that central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters encourage families to have only one child were replaced by copies of detailed regulations that have the right to have a second child and how to apply for authorization.
The city government has deployed family and volunteer planning officials to meet couples at home, and to drag prospectuses under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who wished to have more than one child.
According to the family planner, the answer was disappointing.
Disappointment Response
Although officials in a rural town in the Shanghai suburbs say that they have seen an increase in requests for a second-child couple file after the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, always receives only four to five applications per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, claim that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only about 165 000 -- slightly greater than 2009 but less than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the Family Planning Committee in the Municipality of Caulu in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to have their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years old and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26 years old, said they would love to have two children and are legally allowed there.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and the life insurance given by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners wrongly consider that the single child's policy is a problem of rights, Yang said, a construction engineer whose wife is pregnant seven months from the first child of the couple.
True, we steal the chance of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, Human Resources Manager, said she only wanted a single child because she was a single child herself. "We were the center of the family and had the habit of everyone taking care of us."
We don't usually take care of someone else and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company says it is more crude.
For couples working at two, middle-class, which lowers the birth rate, he says, it is necessary to be selfish and succeed.
20-30-year-olds grew up to see their parents fighting in the early days of capitalist China and they don't want to have this lifestyle themselves, he says.
