The United Nations Group has draft emission reduction plans
The climate conference, sponsored by the United Nations -- which has so far been characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual crimes -- has returned under the light of the ramp on Friday, as a result of the publication of a document highlighting the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden, in the near future.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases has highlighted the remaining obstacles, as long as it has clarified the path to be taken.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from all over the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by a United Nations ad hoc working group, the text does not state how much rich countries would give to the poor to support climate warming in the long run and in the long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how the developed economies and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the rise in global temperature would be willing to tolerate.
It gives a great deal of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General described on UN climate change, Yvo de Boer, as "the full image".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 per cent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations on Friday by promising to provide $3.6 billion a year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
On Friday, however, the same verbal changes have occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, United States Representative for Climate Negotiation, rejected any discussion that required the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration became tougher to China than the Bush administration was, two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions of major developing countries, says Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his remarks an hour after the Chinese Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, He Yafei stated that the US principal negotiator, either lacked "good sense", or was "extremely irresponsible" for having said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China financially to fight climate warming.
With the future economic paths of the major world powers at stake, defects have occurred both in the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle involves more saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States complaining about their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers were fighting to know who should suffer the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make large issuers responsible for their actions.
It's really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, Ulate said, which is also a climate advisor for Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of these countries, more vulnerable to the impact of climate change, indicated that they would continue to put pressure on a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants said that negotiations would lead to a minimum, to political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, has drafted a proposal for a treaty of 24 pages, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of Climate Unit of the European Commission, said that the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the complete political process", partly by what they are now unified and asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Discussions became an urgent matter, while delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the problems in progress before the Heads of Government reached agreement.
High-level officials such as the Minister of the Indian Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Deputy Minister of China have descended from their aircraft and precipitated themselves in the building of the Bella Center to attend meetings in cloze and briefings, in order to make claims that will be considered during the following week.
The true image of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people enter and leave the Palais des congresses every day -- guitar-player activists show night shows mocking countries, betraying themselves, and proposals being written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
Intensity only increases: almost all important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We enter the Great Court, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice-President of the World Conservation Policy.
