Management revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies to its employees has been pointing to the position of consumers prior to the marketing revolution: it is a matter of having employees adhere to "values" determined from above as they once were, to impose on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put forward strategies to conquer markets in the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors comes back regularly!
Demobilisation of employees can lead to mortifying demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects particularly managers.
This demobilisation seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
In fact, the EI "requires all stakeholders ... a proactive approach and a prospective vision"; it requires an undertaking on the part of employees that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would involve putting employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion investigations
The internal opinion surveys – like the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – will they encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many deviations, to do primarily... what it has always done.!
- Then, because of authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic vision of human behavior.
They have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology in the major engineering schools.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old Behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "neurosciences" and widely distributed, at their inst, by the educational institutes and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "lights" (sic) of the engagement of the executives, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr comforts the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, which is not adapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilisation factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires adopting a finalistic vision of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means of achieving some of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, only the studies from the Reasoning Analysis adopt this design of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business by relying on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilisation factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and restore their human resources management "to the place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
