Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is evident from the study "Fecuity and Professional Career of Women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey, conducted in 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have experienced limited careers due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether or not women work and the type of employment they work for.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have little stable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are forced to enter life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women aged 35 to 49 who have fixed jobs have their first child, on average 3.7 years after they have settled in marriage, and this number goes to 4.1 in those who work in the public sector."These data show that women with stable employment have needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which has led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the starting date of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another factor that increases the age of women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those who did elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
