In these bad days and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a disaster are brought back to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage suffered and the cost of repair.
Each disaster is different, and the calculation of the cost of parts and working time can be a long and complex work.
Calculate by hand the cost of a repair of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including the parts and the work force can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the assistance of the latest computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
For this reason, almost 100% of experts use such systems.
Service providers and solutions for the assessment of claims and maintenance are devoted to the collection of information provided by manufacturers, and then process them and offer them to their clients in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, from the North American group Solara, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other companies in competition in the field of evaluation tools and the development of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, so that over the past five years more versions, variants and motorizations have been launched than in the previous 15 years.
When a new car comes out on the market, these companies get to work.
This is very hard work, because we need to catalogue each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and register its price.
In addition, a "intelligent" graphic image is drawn from each model on which you can click on the different parts of a tourism car.
If it is a massively sold model, work can be done within a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a low-sale car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they include information about the Porsches, but not Ferraris or Lamborghini.
With respect to vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99 %.
To carry out the work of documentation and database development, Audatex has eight centres throughout the world (in Spain, France, Germany, Brazil, Mexico, France, China and Japan), each of which specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than 100 technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million annually to develop these databases.
Each month, 2.5 million data is recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows these companies to make different uses and offer various products.
